## What this is

Firebase Android SDK is Google's official open-source Android library that brings Firebase's backend services to Android apps. It provides SDKs for Firestore, Realtime Database, Cloud Storage, Cloud Messaging, Crashlytics, Performance Monitoring, and 15+ other Firebase products—excluding Firebase Authentication and Analytics, which are maintained separately.

### Stack
- **Language(s):** Java and Kotlin
- **Framework / runtime:** Android SDK (API 23+), Gradle (Kotlin DSL), Android Studio
- **Notable libraries:** Firebase Components (dependency injection), Protobuf & Protocol Lite, Guava, Gson, Arrow Android (Kotlin support), Google Cloud protocol buffers

## How it's organized

```
firebase-android-sdk/
  firebase-common/              Shared SDK infrastructure, annotations (@Keep, @KeepForSdk, @PublicApi)
  firebase-components/          Dependency injection & component registry
  firebase-annotations/         Custom annotations for SDK tooling
  
  firebase-firestore/           Cloud Firestore (NoSQL database)
  firebase-database/            Realtime Database
  firebase-storage/             Cloud Storage
  firebase-functions/           Callable Cloud Functions
  firebase-messaging/           Cloud Messaging (FCM)
  firebase-dynamic-links/       Dynamic links
  
  firebase-crashlytics/         Crash reporting
  firebase-crashlytics-gradle/  Gradle plugin for Crashlytics
  firebase-crashlytics-ndk/     Native crash capture (NDK)
  
  firebase-perf/                Performance Monitoring
  firebase-perf-gradle/         Gradle plugin for instrumentation
  firebase-config/              Remote Config
  firebase-sessions/            Session tracking
  firebase-abt/                 A/B Testing
  firebase-installations/       Installation ID service
  firebase-inappmessaging/      In-App Messaging
  firebase-ml-modeldownloader/  ML Model Downloader
  firebase-appdistribution/     App Distribution
  firebase-dataconnect/         DataConnect
  firebase-vertexai/            Vertex AI integration
  
  ai-logic/                     AI logic modules & KSP processor for code generation
  encoders/                     Serialization/deserialization framework
  transport/                    Transport layer for telemetry (CCT backend)
  
  plugins/                      Custom Gradle plugins (Firebase library plugin, CI, publishing)
  ci/                           CI/CD tooling (Python fireci CLI)
  gradle/                       Gradle configuration & version catalog
  integ-testing/                Integration test utilities
  tools/                        Lint tools and utilities
  contributor-docs/             Developer onboarding & architectural docs
```

**How it fits together:** Each Firebase product has its own module (e.g., `firebase-firestore`) that depends on `firebase-common` for shared utilities and `firebase-components` for initialization. The `transport/` layer handles background telemetry delivery via the CCT protocol. Custom Gradle plugins in `plugins/` manage compilation, testing, proguard rules, and publishing. The `encoders/` framework provides serialization throughout the SDK. CI is orchestrated via Python (`ci/fireci/`) for test coordination across JVM unit tests and Firebase Test Lab device tests.

## How to run it

```bash
# Clone with submodules
git clone --recurse-submodules git@github.com:firebase/firebase-android-sdk.git
cd firebase-android-sdk

# Import into Android Studio (Meerkat 2024.3.1+)
# Use Import Project (Gradle) option

# Run unit tests on a single module
./gradlew :firebase-firestore:check

# Run integration tests on emulator
./gradlew :firebase-firestore:connectedCheck

# Run on Firebase Test Lab
./gradlew :firebase-firestore:deviceCheck

# Publish a module locally for integration testing
./gradlew -PprojectsToPublish="firebase-firestore,firebase-functions" \
    publishReleasingLibrariesToMavenLocal

# Format code
./gradlew :firebase-firestore:spotlessApply
```

**Prerequisites:** NDK 21 for `firebase-crashlytics-ndk`; `google-services.json` for integration tests (add to repo root).

